WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:01.560
Let's make another component up here.

00:01.560 --> 00:02.840
We're going to call it pizza.

00:08.000 --> 00:11.840
OK, this is going to be another component.

00:11.840 --> 00:13.040
And we're going to say return.

00:16.440 --> 00:19.320
Well, yeah, we have to do react.createElement return.

00:23.960 --> 00:25.040
This is going to be a div.

00:25.040 --> 00:27.440
It's going to be an empty object here.

00:27.440 --> 00:34.400
We're going to give it an array, just for fun,

00:34.400 --> 00:36.800
because we want to return multiple top-level React

00:36.800 --> 00:37.360
components.

00:37.360 --> 00:38.400
And that's how you do it.

00:38.400 --> 00:40.000
You do it with an array.

00:40.000 --> 00:47.680
React.createElement H1, empty object.

00:47.680 --> 00:51.800
And this is going to be the pepperoni pizza.

00:51.800 --> 00:54.640
Feel free to put in here whatever you want.

00:54.640 --> 00:58.880
If you like a pineapple on your pizza, no judgment here.

01:04.920 --> 01:07.800
So we've now made this pizza component.

01:07.800 --> 01:09.200
You see this is returning an array.

01:09.200 --> 01:13.480
This is the way that you return two siblings as a top-level

01:13.480 --> 01:14.880
component here.

01:14.880 --> 01:17.160
The other way that this could work,

01:17.160 --> 01:19.160
you can actually delete this and have it just

01:19.160 --> 01:28.080
be multiple parameters to the react.createElement function.

01:28.080 --> 01:30.680
Honestly, it doesn't really matter,

01:30.680 --> 01:32.960
because once we start getting into JSX,

01:32.960 --> 01:35.360
it's irrelevant of how it happens.

01:35.360 --> 01:38.040
But just so you know, under the hood,

01:38.040 --> 01:40.720
JSX will convert this to an array, which occasionally

01:40.720 --> 01:45.640
can be useful, or it's at least good to know, or irrelevant.

01:45.640 --> 01:47.880
I don't know, you might forget it, and who cares?

01:47.880 --> 01:50.560
Anyway, an array.

01:50.560 --> 01:52.920
So now we have this array, and we

01:52.920 --> 01:59.600
want to render a bunch of pizzas inside of our app.

01:59.600 --> 02:03.400
So we're also going to turn this into an array.

02:03.400 --> 02:05.400
I'm going to move this createElement inside of it

02:05.400 --> 02:07.080
as the first thing.

02:07.080 --> 02:10.280
And then I'm just going to create a bunch of pizzas.

02:10.280 --> 02:17.240
React.createElement pizza.

02:17.240 --> 02:19.120
And I'm just going to make a couple of those.

02:27.680 --> 02:29.440
So something you might be gathering here,

02:29.440 --> 02:32.480
if it's a string, it's going to literally output

02:32.480 --> 02:36.320
that string to the DOM as a DOM node.

02:36.320 --> 02:41.600
And if it's a function or a React component of some variety,

02:41.600 --> 02:44.640
it's going to try and render that function.

02:44.640 --> 02:46.440
But the cool thing about React is you kind of

02:46.440 --> 02:47.520
get to treat them the same.

02:50.200 --> 02:53.760
Now, you might be asking, well, what

02:53.760 --> 02:57.840
happened to this stuff, right?

02:57.840 --> 02:59.040
You can put it in there.

02:59.040 --> 03:01.320
So this will pass down properties into pizza,

03:01.320 --> 03:03.120
and we'll look about that in just a second.

03:03.120 --> 03:06.400
And you can give pizza children elements as well,

03:06.400 --> 03:07.840
which we'll also talk about later.

03:07.840 --> 03:10.040
But just so you know, it's the same function.

03:10.040 --> 03:12.600
It works exactly the same way.

03:12.600 --> 03:14.720
Because we have nothing to give it as children,

03:14.720 --> 03:15.880
because we have no properties to give it,

03:15.880 --> 03:17.360
we can just omit all of it, which

03:17.360 --> 03:19.160
is what we're doing here.

03:19.160 --> 03:20.200
OK.

03:20.200 --> 03:22.440
So again, my favorite thing to do,

03:22.440 --> 03:25.800
what do we expect to happen here?

03:25.800 --> 03:28.360
And I like to work at the top of the tree, which is app,

03:28.360 --> 03:29.480
and then work my way down.

03:29.480 --> 03:29.980
All right.

03:29.980 --> 03:32.760
So we're going to render into root app.

03:32.760 --> 03:35.400
So we're going to render this.

03:35.400 --> 03:37.000
Then we're going to have a div.

03:37.000 --> 03:38.440
And inside of that div, we're going

03:38.440 --> 03:42.920
to have an H1 with Padre Gino's, which is what we had before.

03:42.920 --> 03:44.400
But then we have pizza here.

03:44.720 --> 03:46.160
So this is going to go into pizza,

03:46.160 --> 03:49.680
and it's going to render an H1 with pepperoni pizza,

03:49.680 --> 03:55.240
and a P with mozzarella cheese and pepperoni.

03:55.240 --> 03:57.360
It does it once.

03:57.360 --> 03:58.960
And then it's going to do it again.

03:58.960 --> 04:05.280
Another H1, another P. And it does so five different times.

04:05.280 --> 04:06.000
So far, so good.

04:06.000 --> 04:07.640
Makes sense?

04:07.640 --> 04:10.680
So how many H1s do you expect?

04:10.680 --> 04:11.960
Mildly a trick question.

04:15.400 --> 04:17.280
Six, right?

04:17.280 --> 04:19.240
Because you're going to have five from the pizza

04:19.240 --> 04:21.000
and then one from Padre Gino's, right?

04:21.000 --> 04:23.360
That's why it says mildly a trick question.

04:23.360 --> 04:25.960
And then how many Ps do you expect?

04:25.960 --> 04:27.440
Five.

04:27.440 --> 04:28.320
All right.

04:28.320 --> 04:29.040
Let's take a look.

04:35.040 --> 04:38.480
A lot of pepperoni pizza.

04:38.480 --> 04:40.280
Pretty cool, though, right?

04:40.280 --> 04:43.280
You might react yelling at you.

04:43.280 --> 04:44.240
Is this about keys?

04:44.640 --> 04:46.440
Just go ahead and straight up ignore react.

04:46.440 --> 04:49.440
It doesn't know what it's talking about.

04:49.440 --> 04:50.560
We'll talk about that.

04:50.560 --> 04:53.400
But for now, just ignore react.

04:53.400 --> 04:54.560
What you're doing is fine.

04:54.560 --> 04:57.200
Now I want to have multiple types of pizza.

04:57.200 --> 05:00.200
I am a connoisseur of pizza, you might call me.

05:00.200 --> 05:02.280
You might not.

05:02.280 --> 05:04.040
So how do we do that?

05:04.040 --> 05:05.880
What's cool is pizza can accept what

05:05.880 --> 05:08.280
these things called props.

05:08.280 --> 05:12.440
Stands for properties, in case you're wondering.

05:12.480 --> 05:14.240
Probably was illuminating to no one.

05:14.240 --> 05:15.840
You probably got that right away.

05:15.840 --> 05:16.360
That's fine.

05:16.360 --> 05:18.360
It made me feel smart to say it.

05:18.360 --> 05:21.680
And we're going to say here on props,

05:21.680 --> 05:25.160
we can pull things off of it that we pass down into it.

05:25.160 --> 05:28.680
So we want to give it whatever the name of the pizza is.

05:28.680 --> 05:31.400
And then we want to give it a description, right?

05:31.400 --> 05:33.760
So we're going to say props.

05:33.760 --> 05:34.560
I call it description.

05:34.560 --> 05:37.440
I did.

05:37.440 --> 05:38.440
So cool.

05:38.440 --> 05:40.080
Now it's a bit more flexible.

05:40.080 --> 05:41.120
I can accept a name.

05:41.120 --> 05:42.440
I can accept a description.

05:42.440 --> 05:47.520
Let's go ahead and add these to our pizzas.

05:47.520 --> 05:52.440
So this is where this object is going to come in handy.

05:52.440 --> 05:54.600
Now we can come in here and say object.

05:54.600 --> 05:57.280
And we're going to give it a name.

05:57.280 --> 06:02.960
And we'll give it, this one can be the pepperoni pizza.

06:02.960 --> 06:07.160
And the description can be, I have

06:07.160 --> 06:09.040
like nice looking descriptions here.

06:09.080 --> 06:10.680
And I'm not going to do that because I

