On the pizza of the day, we have to show it.

07:43.160 --> 07:45.440
On the orders page, we have to show it.

07:45.440 --> 07:48.360
On the past orders page, we have to show it.

07:48.360 --> 07:51.320
And now we just get one pizza component

07:51.320 --> 07:53.280
that if you give it the right information,

07:53.280 --> 07:55.840
it's going to display nicely and encapsulate

07:55.840 --> 08:01.840
all of the logic for making a pizza, right?

08:01.840 --> 08:03.800
It's interesting to look at the history of React

08:03.800 --> 08:05.640
and why it's built this way.

08:05.640 --> 08:09.280
When React was created, the really big things on the market

08:09.280 --> 08:14.280
were model view controllers or model view view models

08:14.280 --> 08:22.040
frameworks, which was like Backbone, old Angular, Knockout.

08:22.040 --> 08:23.680
They all had these kind of like, they

08:23.680 --> 08:26.120
were copying basically what Rails was doing on the back end

08:26.120 --> 08:28.520
and they were trying to ship that logic to the front end.

08:28.520 --> 08:30.920
I wrote lots of it, pretty good code bases.

08:30.920 --> 08:35.400
I mean, I'm not actually going to really talk down too much

08:35.400 --> 08:38.920
to it, but React kind of had this like epiphany.

08:38.920 --> 08:40.720
It's like, you know what's actually really easy

08:40.720 --> 08:42.760
to write websites with?

08:42.760 --> 08:45.000
PHP, right?

08:45.000 --> 08:47.080
The page model really appealed to them

08:47.080 --> 08:49.520
where you have everything kind of mashed together

08:49.520 --> 08:51.240
for small things, right?

08:51.240 --> 08:52.560
So instead of trying to separate,

08:52.560 --> 08:54.800
here's my model that talks to the database,

08:54.800 --> 08:56.440
here's my view of what people look at it,

08:56.440 --> 08:59.400
and here's the view model, which connects the two things,

08:59.400 --> 09:01.840
they were like, let's take the model, the view,

09:01.840 --> 09:03.480
and the view model and shove it together

09:03.480 --> 09:05.040
so you have these components that

09:05.040 --> 09:08.880
contain everything for very small pieces of code.

09:08.880 --> 09:12.400
That was kind of the PHP way unintentionally at the time,

09:12.400 --> 09:16.480
but I'll say that my first job was I was a PHP dev.

09:16.480 --> 09:17.840
I was very productive, right?

09:17.840 --> 09:20.240
I shipped a lot of code very quickly.

09:20.240 --> 09:22.560
So that is the story of React of how

09:22.560 --> 09:24.880
we got this idea of like, we're going to take everything

09:24.880 --> 09:26.040
for these small components and we're

09:26.040 --> 09:28.960
going to shove them together so that you have everything

09:28.960 --> 09:32.000
for one concern in one place.

09:32.000 --> 09:37.040
And it turns out for UIs, that's extremely useful.

09:37.040 --> 09:38.680
Because now we can have this pizza logic,

09:38.680 --> 09:40.960
and instead of having to connect everything together,

09:40.960 --> 09:42.380
we have to connect the view model

09:42.380 --> 09:44.160
to all these different places.

09:44.160 --> 09:46.720
We just say, here's a pizza, and all the logic for pizza

09:46.720 --> 09:48.280
is contained in one space.

09:48.280 --> 09:49.240
That's great.

09:49.240 --> 09:51.680
I obviously have been doing it for a decade,

09:51.680 --> 09:52.480
so I stuck with it.

09:52.480 --> 09:54.920
So it's a really nice way of writing interfaces.

